******
[2] North Carolina
Date: Wed 6 Aug 2014
Source: WNCN [edited]
http://www.wncn.com/story/26212405/2-horses-in-eastern-nc-die-from-mosquito-borne-disease


Within the past 2 weeks, 2 horses -- 1 from Bladen County and 1 from Carteret County -- died after contracting eastern equine encephalomyelitis (EEE) .

Animals can get the disease from an infected mosquito.

Both horses were unvaccinated; the Carteret County horse was euthanized on [21 Jul 2014] and the Bladen County horse died on [2 Aug 2014].

The 2 cases are the 1st reported cases of EEE in horses in North Carolina this year [2014].

"If your horses exhibit any signs of EEE, contact your veterinarian immediately," said State Veterinarian David Marshall in a written release. "Several serious contagious diseases, such as West Nile virus, equine herpesvirus, and rabies, have similar symptoms and should be ruled out."

Earlier this summer [2014], New Hanover County officials reported that the disease was found in a sentinel chicken flock. The state recorded 15 EEE cases in horses in 2013.

EEE causes inflammation or swelling of the brain and spinal cord and is usually fatal. Symptoms include impaired vision, aimless wandering, head pressing, circling, inability to swallow, irregular staggering gait, paralysis, convulsions, and death.

Once a horse has been bitten by an infected mosquito, it may take 3 to 10 days for signs of the disease to appear.

The vaccinations initially require 2 shots, 30 days apart, for horses, mules, and donkeys that have no prior vaccination history. Marshall recommends a booster shot every 6 months.

